  abstract = {抽象的As economic inequality grows, more people stand to benefit from wealth redistribution. Yet in many countries, increasing inequality has not produced growing support for redistribution, and people often appear to vote against their economic interest. Here we suggest that two cognitive tendencies contribute to these paradoxical voting patterns. First, people gauge their income through social comparison, and those comparisons are usually made to similar others. Second, people are insensitive to large numbers, which leads them to underestimate the gap between themselves and the very wealthy. These two tendencies can help explain why subjective income is normally distributed (therefore most people think they are middle class) and partly explain why many people who would benefit from redistribution oppose it. We support our model’s assumptions using survey data, a controlled experiment, and agent-based modeling. Our model sheds light on the cognitive barriers to reducing inequality.随着经济不平等的加剧，更多的人将从财富重新分配中受益。然而在许多国家，日益加剧的不平等并没有带来对再分配的越来越多的支持，而且人们似乎常常投票反对他们的经济利益。在这里，我们认为两种认知倾向导致了这些自相矛盾的投票模式。首先，人们通过社会比较来衡量自己的收入，这些比较通常是与类似的其他人进行的。其次，人们对数字不敏感，这导致他们低估了自己与富人之间的差距。这两种倾向可以帮助解释为什么主观收入是正态分配的（因此大多数人认为自己是中产阶级），并部分解释为什么许多将从再分配中受益的人反对它。我们使用调查数据、受控实验和基于主体的建模来支持模型的假设。我们的模型揭示了减少不平等的认知障碍。},
